{"title_page": "Greenbelt (Ottawa)", "text_new": "{{Infobox protected area\n| name = Mike wazowski (Ottawa)\n| iucn_category = \n| photo = Greenbelt Ottawa.jpg\n| map_image = ottawagreenbelt.PNG\n| map_caption = Map of Ottawa showing the Greenbelt surrounding the urban core\n| location = Eastern Ontario, Canada\n| nearest_city = [[Ottawa]]\n| nearest_town = \n| coordinates = \n| area_km2 = 203.5\n| established = 1956\n| visitation_num = \n| visitation_year = \n| governing_body = [[National Capital Commission]]\n| url = http://ncc-ccn.gc.ca/places-to-visit/greenbelt\n}}\n\nThe '''Greenbelt''' is a {{convert|203.5|km2|sqmi|adj=on}} protected  [[green belt]] traversing [[Ottawa]],[[Ontario]], Canada.  It includes green space, forests, farms, and wetlands from [[Shirleys Bay]] in the west and to [[Green's Creek (Ontario)|Green's Creek]] in the east. The [[National Capital Commission]] (NCC) owns and manages {{convert|149.5|km2|sqmi}}, and the rest is held by other federal government departments and private interests.<ref name=\"GHC\" /> Real estate development within the Greenbelt is strictly controlled.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\n==History==\nThe Greenbelt was proposed by [[Jacques Gr\u00e9ber]] in 1950 as part of his master plan for Ottawa, and the federal government started expropriating land in 1956. Its original purpose included the prevention of [[urban sprawl]] (which was threatening the rural areas surrounding the city), as well as to provide open space for the future development of farms, natural areas and government campuses.<ref name=\"GHC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.canadascapital.gc.ca/places-to-visit/greenbelt/about-national-capital-greenbelt |title=About the National Capital Greenbelt |publisher=National Capital Commission |accessdate=2013-04-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130531074418/http://www.canadascapital.gc.ca/places-to-visit/greenbelt/about-national-capital-greenbelt |archive-date=2013-05-31 |url-status=dead }}</ref> At the time, the greenbelt was \"intended to circumscribe an area large enough for the accommodation of some 500,000 persons. The inner limit was chosen by considering what area could be economically provided with municipal services.\"<ref>Eggleston, W., 1961. ''The Queen's Choice.'' The National Capital Commission, Ottawa, Ontario, 325 pp.</ref>\n\n==Development==\nThe City of Ottawa is undergoing{{When|date=February 2020}} an Official Plan Review which, among other things, examines the need for additional land for urban purposes. It considers whether a discussion of urban land should include the option of some development within the Greenbelt and it is intended that this discussion will feed into the NCC\u2019s review of the Greenbelt Master Plan. All views expressed in [the] White Paper are those of the City of Ottawa and not those of the National Capital Commission <ref>[http://www.ottawa.ca/residents/public_consult/beyond_2020/papers/greenbelt_white_paper/index_en.html City of Ottawa Greenbelt Whitepaper]{{dead link|fix-attempted=yes|date=December 2018}}</ref> which owns and operates the Greenbelt. The City of Ottawa has identified more than {{convert|13700|acre|km2}} of the Greenbelt, worth about $1.6 billion, that could be developed, and in their view, without damaging its overall integrity.<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://pondpine.blogspot.com/2008/06/ottawa-greenbelt-development-under.html Ottawa Housing Market: Ottawa Greenbelt Development Under Review]</ref> Environment Minister [[Jim Prentice]], opposed development in what he considered an important part of the city's heritage. Prentice vowed to fight any such move.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nIn 2020, the ''[[Ottawa Citizen]]'' described the Greenbelt as \"a failed attempt to contain growth, not a collection of natural treasures\", and supported development within the Greenbelt because \"it would give the city the land capacity it requires and deliver all the environmental, transportation and practical benefits that environment groups envision\", while Ottawa city staff stated \"Expanding urban lands within the Greenbelt is a more efficient use of resources than beyond it.\"<ref>{{cite news | last = Denley | first = Randall | date = February 4, 2020 | title = Denley: If Ottawa is Serious About its Climate Emergency, it's Time to Consider Developing the Greenbelt | url = https://ottawacitizen.com/opinion/columnists/denley-if-ottawa-is-serious-about-its-climate-emergency-its-time-to-consider-developing-the-greenbelt | work = Ottawa Citizen}}</ref>\n\n==Wildlife==\n{{unreferenced section|date=February 2020}}\n[[File:Great Crested Flycatcher.jpg|thumb|right|[[Great crested flycatcher]] (Myiarchus crinitus), [[Mer Bleue Conservation Area]].]]\nThe Greenbelt is home to a variety of wildlife:\n\n*Mammals: [[bat]], [[American black bear|bear]], [[North American beaver|beaver]], [[coyote]], [[Eastern cottontail|cottontail rabbit]], [[Fisher (animal)|fisher]], [[muskrat]], [[North American porcupine|porcupine]], [[raccoon]], [[red fox]], [[American red squirrel|red squirrel]], [[snowshoe hare]], [[Striped skunk|skunk]], [[white-tailed deer]], rarely [[moose]]\n*Birds: [[barred owl]], [[screech owl]], [[great grey owl]], [[Canada goose]], [[sandhill crane]], [[great blue heron]], [[red-tailed hawk]], [[American kestrel]], [[spruce grouse]], [[woodcock]], [[blue jay]], [[chickadee]]\n*Insects: [[Stick insect|walking stick]], [[European mantis|praying mantis]], [[butterflies]]\n*Reptiles/Amphibians: [[common garter snake]], [[painted turtle]], [[Common snapping turtle|snapping turtle]]\n\n==Places of interest==\n{{GeoGroup}}\n[[File:Greenbelt marker.jpg|right|100px|thumb|Trail marker]]\nPlaces of interest within the Greenbelt are from east to west:\n*[[Green's Creek (Ontario)|Green's Creek]] Conservation Area \u2013 a nature reserve of a small tributary of the Ottawa River, cutting through a lush clay valley.  <small>{{coord|45|28|00|N|75|34|35|W|display=inline}}</small>\n*Hornets Nest soccer fields \u2013 11 soccer fields and an [[air-supported structure|air-supported dome]] for indoor soccer.  <small>{{coord|45|26|35|N|75|34|35|W|display=inline}}</small>\n*Pine View Golf Course \u2013 36-hole public golf course  <small>{{coord|45|25|50|N|75|35|50|W|display=inline}}</small>\n*[[Mer Bleue Conservation Area]] \u2013 33&nbsp;km\u00b2 sphagnum peat bog. There are some 20&nbsp;km of walking trails, including a 1.2&nbsp;km boardwalk, through a remarkable [[taiga|boreal]]-like ecosystem normally not found this far south. Stunted [[black spruce]], [[tamarack]], together with bog [[rosemary]], [[blueberry]], and [[Common Cottongrass|cottongrass]], are some of the unusual species that have adapted to the acidic waters of the bog. The Mer Bleue bog (French for ''Blue Sea'') got its name from the autumn morning fogs that make it appear as a blue sea.  <small>{{coord|45|24|00|N|75|30|00|W|display=inline}}</small>\n*Pine Grove Forest \u2013 12&nbsp;km\u00b2 of mixed-use forest for hiking, wildlife reserve, and [[forestry]].  <small>{{coord|45|21|30|N|75|36|00|W|display=inline}}</small>\n*Conroy Pit \u2013 a 1.1&nbsp;km\u00b2 site on a former sand/gravel pit off [[Conroy Road (Ottawa)|Conroy Road]] near [[Hunt Club Road (Ottawa)|Hunt Club Road]], now used primarily as an off-leash dog park and for tobogganing in the winter. It has several kilometres of urban forest trails and wide open areas. The north end of the pit features a large toboggan hill.  <small>{{coord|45|21|30|N|75|37|30|W|display=inline}}</small>\n*Hylands Golf Club \u2013 36-hole public golf course  <small>{{coord|45|19|00|N|75|38|35|W|display=inline}}</small>\n*[[Ottawa Macdonald-Cartier International Airport|Macdonald-Cartier International Airport]] \u2013 Ottawa's main airport for domestic, international, and general aviation.  <small>{{coord|45|19|30|N|75|40|00|W|display=inline}}</small>\n*[[Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada|Agriculture Canada]] Research Farms \u2013 17&nbsp;km\u00b2 site for research in animal disease prevention and treatment.  <small>{{coord|45|19|08|N|75|45|12|W|display=inline}}</small>\n*The Log Farm \u2013 a restored homestead from 1857, with guided tours.  <small>{{coord|45|17|59|N|75|47|50|W|display=inline}}</small>\n*Bruce Pit \u2013 a second former sand/gravel pit off [[Cedarview Road (Ottawa)|Cedarview Road]] between [[Hunt Club Road (Ottawa)|Hunt Club Road]] and [[Baseline Road (Ottawa)|Baseline Road]]. It is now used as an off-leash dog park, and has a cross-country trail system and a toboggan hill.  <small>{{coord|45|19|30|N|75|48|00|W|display=inline}}</small>\n*Lime Kiln (Trail) \u2013 Trail to remains of 19th-century Flood industrial [[Lime (material)|lime]] [[kiln]].<small>{{coord|45|17|13.7|N|75|48|48.8|W|display=inline}}</small>\n*Stony Swamp Conservation Area \u2013 20&nbsp;km\u00b2 of provincially significant wetland.  It is also the largest forested area within the Greenbelt<ref>{{cite web|title=Stony Swamp|url=http://www.canadascapital.gc.ca/places-to-visit/greenbelt/stony-swamp|work=The National Capital Greenbelt|publisher=National Capital Commission|accessdate=7 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121228012731/http://www.canadascapital.gc.ca/places-to-visit/greenbelt/stony-swamp|archive-date=28 December 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> and is popular for hiking and outdoor recreation.  It is also the study area for the [[Macoun Field Club]].<small>{{coord|45|18|00|N|75|50|20|W|display=inline}}</small>\n*[[Wesley Clover Parks]] (formerly the Nepean National Equestrian Park  <small>{{coord|45|20|22|N|75|51|10|W|display=inline}}</small> and the Ottawa Municipal Campground  <small>{{coord|45|19|50|N|75|52|00|W|display=inline}}</small>) - an equestrian facility and public campground with 127 serviced sites\n*The 19th Tee Driving Range \u2013 golf driving range and 18 hole mini-putt park.  <small>{{coord|45|20|43|N|75|52|38|W|display=inline}}</small>\n*[[Connaught National Army Cadet Summer Training Centre]] \u2013 Military and cadet training centre, also used by private shooting associations.  <small>{{coord|45|21|40|N|75|54|00|W|display=inline}}</small>\n*[[Shirleys Bay]] \u2013 an important wetland on the Ottawa River, home to migratory birds and water fowl. This location is ideally suited for bird watching.  <small>{{coord|45|23|00|N|75|55|00|W|display=inline}}</small>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Ontario}}\n* [[Greenbelt (Golden Horseshoe)]] - greenbelt surrounding the Greater Toronto Area\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[https://ncc-ccn.gc.ca/places/greenbelt National Capital Commission]\n*[https://ncc-ccn.maps.arcgis.com/apps/MapTour/index.html?appid=78ef7172cbd84cc79c0544dd3eb6d8d9# interactive map]\n*[https://www.ottawatourism.ca/member/national-capital-greenbelt-national-capital-commission/ Ottawa Tourism and Convention Authority]\n\n{{Ottawa landmarks}}\n{{Ontario parks}}\n\n[[Category:Geography of Ottawa]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Ontario]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Ottawa]]\n[[Category:Green belts|O]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox protected area\n| name = Greenbelt (Ottawa)\n| iucn_category = \n| photo = Greenbelt Ottawa.jpg\n| map_image = ottawagreenbelt.PNG\n| map_caption = Map of Ottawa showing the Greenbelt surrounding the urban core\n| location = Eastern Ontario, Canada\n| nearest_city = [[Ottawa]]\n| nearest_town = \n| coordinates = \n| area_km2 = 203.5\n| established = 1956\n| visitation_num = \n| visitation_year = \n| governing_body = [[National Capital Commission]]\n| url = http://ncc-ccn.gc.ca/places-to-visit/greenbelt\n}}\n\nThe '''Greenbelt''' is a {{convert|203.5|km2|sqmi|adj=on}} protected  [[green belt]] traversing [[Ottawa]],[[Ontario]], Canada.  It includes green space, forests, farms, and wetlands from [[Shirleys Bay]] in the west and to [[Green's Creek (Ontario)|Green's Creek]] in the east. The [[National Capital Commission]] (NCC) owns and manages {{convert|149.5|km2|sqmi}}, and the rest is held by other federal government departments and private interests.<ref name=\"GHC\" /> Real estate development within the Greenbelt is strictly controlled.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\n==History==\nThe Greenbelt was proposed by [[Jacques Gr\u00e9ber]] in 1950 as part of his master plan for Ottawa, and the federal government started expropriating land in 1956. Its original purpose included the prevention of [[urban sprawl]] (which was threatening the rural areas surrounding the city), as well as to provide open space for the future development of farms, natural areas and government campuses.<ref name=\"GHC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.canadascapital.gc.ca/places-to-visit/greenbelt/about-national-capital-greenbelt |title=About the National Capital Greenbelt |publisher=National Capital Commission |accessdate=2013-04-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130531074418/http://www.canadascapital.gc.ca/places-to-visit/greenbelt/about-national-capital-greenbelt |archive-date=2013-05-31 |url-status=dead }}</ref> At the time, the greenbelt was \"intended to circumscribe an area large enough for the accommodation of some 500,000 persons. The inner limit was chosen by considering what area could be economically provided with municipal services.\"<ref>Eggleston, W., 1961. ''The Queen's Choice.'' The National Capital Commission, Ottawa, Ontario, 325 pp.</ref>\n\n==Development==\nThe City of Ottawa is undergoing{{When|date=February 2020}} an Official Plan Review which, among other things, examines the need for additional land for urban purposes. It considers whether a discussion of urban land should include the option of some development within the Greenbelt and it is intended that this discussion will feed into the NCC\u2019s review of the Greenbelt Master Plan. All views expressed in [the] White Paper are those of the City of Ottawa and not those of the National Capital Commission <ref>[http://www.ottawa.ca/residents/public_consult/beyond_2020/papers/greenbelt_white_paper/index_en.html City of Ottawa Greenbelt Whitepaper]{{dead link|fix-attempted=yes|date=December 2018}}</ref> which owns and operates the Greenbelt. The City of Ottawa has identified more than {{convert|13700|acre|km2}} of the Greenbelt, worth about $1.6 billion, that could be developed, and in their view, without damaging its overall integrity.<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://pondpine.blogspot.com/2008/06/ottawa-greenbelt-development-under.html Ottawa Housing Market: Ottawa Greenbelt Development Under Review]</ref> Environment Minister [[Jim Prentice]], opposed development in what he considered an important part of the city's heritage. Prentice vowed to fight any such move.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nIn 2020, the ''[[Ottawa Citizen]]'' described the Greenbelt as \"a failed attempt to contain growth, not a collection of natural treasures\", and supported development within the Greenbelt because \"it would give the city the land capacity it requires and deliver all the environmental, transportation and practical benefits that environment groups envision\", while Ottawa city staff stated \"Expanding urban lands within the Greenbelt is a more efficient use of resources than beyond it.\"<ref>{{cite news | last = Denley | first = Randall | date = February 4, 2020 | title = Denley: If Ottawa is Serious About its Climate Emergency, it's Time to Consider Developing the Greenbelt | url = https://ottawacitizen.com/opinion/columnists/denley-if-ottawa-is-serious-about-its-climate-emergency-its-time-to-consider-developing-the-greenbelt | work = Ottawa Citizen}}</ref>\n\n==Wildlife==\n{{unreferenced section|date=February 2020}}\n[[File:Great Crested Flycatcher.jpg|thumb|right|[[Great crested flycatcher]] (Myiarchus crinitus), [[Mer Bleue Conservation Area]].]]\nThe Greenbelt is home to a variety of wildlife:\n\n*Mammals: [[bat]], [[American black bear|bear]], [[North American beaver|beaver]], [[coyote]], [[Eastern cottontail|cottontail rabbit]], [[Fisher (animal)|fisher]], [[muskrat]], [[North American porcupine|porcupine]], [[raccoon]], [[red fox]], [[American red squirrel|red squirrel]], [[snowshoe hare]], [[Striped skunk|skunk]], [[white-tailed deer]], rarely [[moose]]\n*Birds: [[barred owl]], [[screech owl]], [[great grey owl]], [[Canada goose]], [[sandhill crane]], [[great blue heron]], [[red-tailed hawk]], [[American kestrel]], [[spruce grouse]], [[woodcock]], [[blue jay]], [[chickadee]]\n*Insects: [[Stick insect|walking stick]], [[European mantis|praying mantis]], [[butterflies]]\n*Reptiles/Amphibians: [[common garter snake]], [[painted turtle]], [[Common snapping turtle|snapping turtle]]\n\n==Places of interest==\n{{GeoGroup}}\n[[File:Greenbelt marker.jpg|right|100px|thumb|Trail marker]]\nPlaces of interest within the Greenbelt are from east to west:\n*[[Green's Creek (Ontario)|Green's Creek]] Conservation Area \u2013 a nature reserve of a small tributary of the Ottawa River, cutting through a lush clay valley.  <small>{{coord|45|28|00|N|75|34|35|W|display=inline}}</small>\n*Hornets Nest soccer fields \u2013 11 soccer fields and an [[air-supported structure|air-supported dome]] for indoor soccer.  <small>{{coord|45|26|35|N|75|34|35|W|display=inline}}</small>\n*Pine View Golf Course \u2013 36-hole public golf course  <small>{{coord|45|25|50|N|75|35|50|W|display=inline}}</small>\n*[[Mer Bleue Conservation Area]] \u2013 33&nbsp;km\u00b2 sphagnum peat bog. There are some 20&nbsp;km of walking trails, including a 1.2&nbsp;km boardwalk, through a remarkable [[taiga|boreal]]-like ecosystem normally not found this far south. Stunted [[black spruce]], [[tamarack]], together with bog [[rosemary]], [[blueberry]], and [[Common Cottongrass|cottongrass]], are some of the unusual species that have adapted to the acidic waters of the bog. The Mer Bleue bog (French for ''Blue Sea'') got its name from the autumn morning fogs that make it appear as a blue sea.  <small>{{coord|45|24|00|N|75|30|00|W|display=inline}}</small>\n*Pine Grove Forest \u2013 12&nbsp;km\u00b2 of mixed-use forest for hiking, wildlife reserve, and [[forestry]].  <small>{{coord|45|21|30|N|75|36|00|W|display=inline}}</small>\n*Conroy Pit \u2013 a 1.1&nbsp;km\u00b2 site on a former sand/gravel pit off [[Conroy Road (Ottawa)|Conroy Road]] near [[Hunt Club Road (Ottawa)|Hunt Club Road]], now used primarily as an off-leash dog park and for tobogganing in the winter. It has several kilometres of urban forest trails and wide open areas. The north end of the pit features a large toboggan hill.  <small>{{coord|45|21|30|N|75|37|30|W|display=inline}}</small>\n*Hylands Golf Club \u2013 36-hole public golf course  <small>{{coord|45|19|00|N|75|38|35|W|display=inline}}</small>\n*[[Ottawa Macdonald-Cartier International Airport|Macdonald-Cartier International Airport]] \u2013 Ottawa's main airport for domestic, international, and general aviation.  <small>{{coord|45|19|30|N|75|40|00|W|display=inline}}</small>\n*[[Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada|Agriculture Canada]] Research Farms \u2013 17&nbsp;km\u00b2 site for research in animal disease prevention and treatment.  <small>{{coord|45|19|08|N|75|45|12|W|display=inline}}</small>\n*The Log Farm \u2013 a restored homestead from 1857, with guided tours.  <small>{{coord|45|17|59|N|75|47|50|W|display=inline}}</small>\n*Bruce Pit \u2013 a second former sand/gravel pit off [[Cedarview Road (Ottawa)|Cedarview Road]] between [[Hunt Club Road (Ottawa)|Hunt Club Road]] and [[Baseline Road (Ottawa)|Baseline Road]]. It is now used as an off-leash dog park, and has a cross-country trail system and a toboggan hill.  <small>{{coord|45|19|30|N|75|48|00|W|display=inline}}</small>\n*Lime Kiln (Trail) \u2013 Trail to remains of 19th-century Flood industrial [[Lime (material)|lime]] [[kiln]].<small>{{coord|45|17|13.7|N|75|48|48.8|W|display=inline}}</small>\n*Stony Swamp Conservation Area \u2013 20&nbsp;km\u00b2 of provincially significant wetland.  It is also the largest forested area within the Greenbelt<ref>{{cite web|title=Stony Swamp|url=http://www.canadascapital.gc.ca/places-to-visit/greenbelt/stony-swamp|work=The National Capital Greenbelt|publisher=National Capital Commission|accessdate=7 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121228012731/http://www.canadascapital.gc.ca/places-to-visit/greenbelt/stony-swamp|archive-date=28 December 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> and is popular for hiking and outdoor recreation.  It is also the study area for the [[Macoun Field Club]].<small>{{coord|45|18|00|N|75|50|20|W|display=inline}}</small>\n*[[Wesley Clover Parks]] (formerly the Nepean National Equestrian Park  <small>{{coord|45|20|22|N|75|51|10|W|display=inline}}</small> and the Ottawa Municipal Campground  <small>{{coord|45|19|50|N|75|52|00|W|display=inline}}</small>) - an equestrian facility and public campground with 127 serviced sites\n*The 19th Tee Driving Range \u2013 golf driving range and 18 hole mini-putt park.  <small>{{coord|45|20|43|N|75|52|38|W|display=inline}}</small>\n*[[Connaught National Army Cadet Summer Training Centre]] \u2013 Military and cadet training centre, also used by private shooting associations.  <small>{{coord|45|21|40|N|75|54|00|W|display=inline}}</small>\n*[[Shirleys Bay]] \u2013 an important wetland on the Ottawa River, home to migratory birds and water fowl. This location is ideally suited for bird watching.  <small>{{coord|45|23|00|N|75|55|00|W|display=inline}}</small>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Ontario}}\n* [[Greenbelt (Golden Horseshoe)]] - greenbelt surrounding the Greater Toronto Area\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[https://ncc-ccn.gc.ca/places/greenbelt National Capital Commission]\n*[https://ncc-ccn.maps.arcgis.com/apps/MapTour/index.html?appid=78ef7172cbd84cc79c0544dd3eb6d8d9# interactive map]\n*[https://www.ottawatourism.ca/member/national-capital-greenbelt-national-capital-commission/ Ottawa Tourism and Convention Authority]\n\n{{Ottawa landmarks}}\n{{Ontario parks}}\n\n[[Category:Geog